    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-04-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-04-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="911"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d911">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">390.1115A/1543: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-04-14">April 14,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received April 14—11:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2339. American interests—Far East internees. Department’s 465, February 24.
                    Consulate Shanghai telegraphs: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Internment measures<note n="17" xml:id="d911fn17">For message informing
                                the Department of general internment of Americans in China, see
                                telegram No. 743, February 1, from the Minister in Switzerland, <ref
                                    target="#pg_959">p. 959</ref>.</note> still process execution,
                            therefore impossible furnish information desired until arrested persons
                            all interned. Similarly unable communicate names 200 Americans who will
                            probably be liberated (requested Department’s 525, March 4<note n="18"
                                xml:id="d911fn18">Not printed.</note>). Will send soonest
                            possible.</p>
                        <p>Reference system relief payments (Department’s 465, paragraph 2), relief
                            paid interned Americans occupied China, according Department’s 1202,
                            February 14, 1942,<note n="19" xml:id="d911fn19">
                                <ref target="frus1942v01#pg_262">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 262</ref>.</note> in principle
                            considered loans but Japanese authorities fear American Government will
                            eventually demand repayment not from beneficiaries but from detaining
                            power.</p>
                        <p>For this reason all efforts find practical solution for payment relief to
                            internees meets opposition Japanese authorities. To reassure them this
                            respect and permit effective assistance internees, recommend
                            authorization declare payments made on basis paragraph 15 Department’s
                            1202 be considered gifts not loans of American Government.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
